(155, 1, '2021-07-08 08:12:27', '2021-07-08 08:12:27', 'What is Addiction?\r\n\r\nAddiction is a mental disorder characterized by the obsessive use of a rewarding substance or activity despite negative consequences. This complicated disorder, which is influenced by a person\'s genes and environment, is frequently referred to as a mental disorder.\r\n\r\nIndividuals who develop an addiction may not be aware that their behavior is causing issues for themselves and others because addiction affects the brain\'s executive processes, which are located in the prefrontal cortex. The pursuit of the substance\'s or behavior\'s pleasurable benefits may come to dominate an individual\'s actions over time.\r\n\r\nCauses of Addiction\r\n\r\nPeople engage in potentially addictive behaviors in order to feel pleasure, and the reinforcing effect of these activities may modify brain chemistry over time, resulting in an unconscious desire to repeat the habit.\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Genetics</li>\r\n 	<li>Mental health</li>\r\n 	<li>Past traumas</li>\r\n 	<li>Pain</li>\r\n 	<li>Stress</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTreatment of Addiction\r\n\r\nMotivational Interviewing is a short-term therapy procedure that can help a person address treatment and develop and maintain motivation for change.\r\n\r\nFamily therapy helps individuals in rebuilding any family connections that have been affected and establishing more supportive ones.\r\n\r\nAn individual\'s treatment plan may include life skills training, including employability skills.', 'Addiction', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '154-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-07-08 08:12:27', '2021-07-08 08:12:27', '', 154, 'http://localhost/aira/?p=155', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
