(242, 1, '2021-07-09 02:59:50', '2021-07-09 02:59:50', 'What is anxiety?\r\nAnxiety disorders are serious mental illnesses that cause persistent anxiety or fear, which can worsen over time. We all experience anxiety from time to time, but with an anxiety disorder, the anxiety is more persistent and has a significant negative impact on a person\'s quality of life.\r\n\r\nTypes of Anxiety Disorders\r\nGeneralized anxiety disorder (GAD) is a specific type of anxiety disorder. Most individuals worry about their health, job, money, and family from time to time, but persons with GAD worry about these things and more in a persistent, excessive, and intense way.\r\nObsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) is a mental health illness characterized by obsessions and compulsions. Because patients with OCD typically experience extreme anxiety as a result of obsessive thoughts, it was previously characterized as an anxiety disorder. They may also engage in complex routines in an attempt to ease the distress brought on by obsessive thoughts.\r\nPanic Disorder. A person suffering from panic disorder may have symptoms such as intense terror, rapid breathing, and a fast heart rate. These attacks can occur unexpectedly and for no apparent cause in people with panic disorder, but they can also be triggered by a triggering event or scenario.\r\nPost-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) is a mental health illness in which people suffer from a wide range of symptoms after experiencing a traumatic event. Flashbacks, nightmares, intrusive thoughts, anxiety, avoidance, mood, and thinking changes are all possible.\r\nSocial anxiety disorder (SAD) is a mental health condition characterized by a fear of being judged badly in social situations, such as performing or speaking in front of everyone.\r\n\r\nCauses of Anxiety\r\nResearchers are discovering more about these links all the time.\r\nImagining the future\r\nGenetics\r\nEnvironment\r\nIntense stress level\r\nBrain changes\r\nTrauma\r\n\r\nTreatment of Anxiety\r\nAnxiety problems are typically treated successfully with psychotherapy and lifestyle changes, either alone or in combination with medication. One of the most successful treatments is cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT), which is targeted at an individual\'s specific worries. Patients are taught to question the faulty mental patterns that cause them so much pain.', 'Anxiety', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '161-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-07-09 02:59:50', '2021-07-09 02:59:50', '', 161, 'http://localhost/aira/?p=242', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
